Step 1 — Open AWS Console
Search:
CodePipeline
Click Create pipeline.
In AWS search bar type:
CodePipeline
Step 2 — Pipeline Name
Enter:
devops-pipeline
Step 3 — Creation Option
Choose:
Build custom pipeline
Why?
Because templates like ECR / ECS need advanced services.
Step 4 — Source Provider
Choose:
GitHub (via GitHub App)
Step 5 — Create GitHub Connection
Connection name:
github-connection
Click:
Connect to GitHub
Authorize GitHub account.
Step 6 — Repository Selection
Choose repository in exact format:
Dik28/devops-lab
Important Teaching Point
Repository format must be:
account/repository-name
Step 7 — Branch Selection
Choose:
main
Why Branch Matters
AWS only monitors selected branch.
Step 8 — Trigger Option
Keep:
Detect changes automatically
Internal Working
GitHub webhook created automatically
Step 9 — Build Stage
Skip build stage (for beginner lab).
Why Skip?
No compilation required for simple file demo.
Step 10 — Deploy Stage
Choose deploy provider:
Amazon S3
Step 11 — Select Bucket
Choose bucket:
diksha-devops-bucket-2026
(or student bucket name)
Step 12 — S3 Object Key
Enter:
pipeline-output.zip
Step 13 — Check Extract Option
Extract file before deploy
Why Extract?

Without extract:
zip file stored only
With extract:
actual files visible in bucket
Step 14 — Create Pipeline
Click:
Create pipeline
Step 15 — First Run
Pipeline runs automatically.
Students observe:
Source stage
Deploy stage
Step 16 — Test Repository Trigger (Most Important)
Go to GitHub.
Edit:
app.txt
Add:
Pipeline trigger test
Commit change.
